<DOC><DOCNO> AP880928-0182 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 2043EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Heard     09-28 0175</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Heard,0181</SECOND><HEAD>Jazz Drummer J.C. Heard Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jazz drummer J.C. Heard, who performedwith many of the world's best-known jazz musicians, has died. Hewas 71.   Bonnie Niebel, a spokeswoman for William Beaumont Hospital, saidHeard died there Tuesday night. She said she did not know the cause.   Heard had been scheduled to appear Wednesday night in concertwith his friend, trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie. Heard's agent, JimFleming of Ann Arbor, said attempts were being made to see that theconcert Wednesday night and one Thursday go on.   Heard performs on two current albums, ``Some of This, Some ofThat'' and oen on which he accompanied pianist Mark ``Mr. B'' Braun.   ``He was the consummate professional,'' Ron Brooks, a bassplayer and owner of The Bird of Paradise in Ann Arbor, where Heardfrequently played, said Wednesday. ``He was a great model for youngmusicians.''   Brooks said Heard's wife was visiting friends in Europe whenHeard was stricken. The Heards had been living in Southfield.   Funeral arrangements were pending.</TEXT></DOC>